        <exercise id="fs-id3101625" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1849112">    <para id="import-auto-id2616385">There is relatively little empty space between atoms in solids and liquids, so that the average density of an atom is about the same as matter on a macroscopic scale—approximately <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:msup><m:mtext>kg/m</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>. The nucleus of an atom has a radius about <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>5</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow></m:math> that of the atom and contains nearly all the mass of the entire atom. (a) What is the approximate density of a nucleus? (b) One remnant of a supernova, called a neutron star, can have the density of a nucleus. What would be the radius of a neutron star with a mass 10 times that of our Sun (the radius of the Sun is <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>7</m:mn><m:mo stretchy="false">×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>8</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>m</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>)?</para></problem>
<solution id="eip-id1168220523090"><para id="eip-id1168220528222">(a) <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>18</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:msup><m:mtext>kg/m</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math></para><para id="eip-id2324719">(b) <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mo stretchy="false">×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>4</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>m</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math></para></solution></exercise></section>
